Working with files and images in Markdown can be annoying. If you're blogging, you need to make sure the images get uploaded somewhere on the web so they can be served to your readers. If you're just taking notes, your editor needs some kind of support for images; and if you switch editors, your new one had better be able to import them.

**Wouldn't it be great if I could take an image that I have in my clipboard and turn it into a Markdown image snippet, without having to worry about an image file?**

I already use [TextExpander](https://geo.itunes.apple.com/us/app/textexpander/id1075927186?ign-mpt=uo%25253D4&at=11laRZ&ct=afp15&_ga=2.74739922.1732616035.1506452298-884175469.1506452298&mt=8) to help me with regular Markdown images, so why not?

For regular images, I expand `mimg` to `![](%clipboard)`. This takes whatever is in my clipboard, and wraps an image tag around it.

We're going to use shell scripting to get the same effect with a full image in the clipboard. We'll take the image payload, get it out of the clipboard, base64 encode it, and use that as a data string for the image.

# Caveats 

* This will be a separate command from the regular image one above.
* The markdown files will have big data blobs in them.
  * I'm not sure if I'll like the tradeoff of not having to deal with extra files. Time will tell.
* I've only tested this on a Mac. [¯\\\_(ツ)\_/¯](https://media.giphy.com/media/d0SEajOmMna1i/giphy.gif)

# Setup

1. Unfortunately, the built-in `pbpaste` can't help us. Install [`pngpaste`](https://github.com/jcsalterego/pngpaste). If you're using [brew](https://brew.sh/) (you should be), install with: `brew install pngpaste`
2. Create a new expander in your weapon of choice. I prefer TextExpander, but you can get the same effect using [Dash](https://kapeli.com/dash), `bash` aliases, or any equivalent that supports running a bash script. This could be cleaner, but it works. Have it expand to:
    ```bash
    #! /bin/bash
    a="\![](data:image/png;base64,"
    b=$(/usr/local/bin/pngpaste - | base64)
    c=")"
    echo $a$b$c
    ```
3. Make sure the type is `shell script`.
4. Give it an alias. I use `pimg` (paste image).

# Use

1. Get an image into your clipboard. I like [CloudApp](https://www.getcloudapp.com/) for screenshots.
2. Type `pimg` wherever you want the markdown dropped in.
3. Profit.

Enjoy!
